to talk to you about your test.

04:40.530 --> 04:41.531
Sure.

04:42.199 --> 04:43.951
Now, I know you
had a little help.

04:44.034 --> 04:47.038
Well, I mean, I didn't cheat,
if that's what you mean.

04:47.120 --> 04:49.464
I'm just saying I know
you had a little help.

04:49.539 --> 04:51.041
A lot of people did.

04:53.168 --> 04:55.136
Well, be that
as it may...

04:55.212 --> 04:57.055
I mean, I'll take it
over again if you want,

04:57.214 --> 04:59.091
but, like, what
would be the point?

04:59.299 --> 05:01.176
It's not like I'm
ever gonna actually

05:01.301 --> 05:03.178
need to know this
stuff in my daily life.

05:03.261 --> 05:06.265
Well, that's just not
necessarily true, Lisa.

05:06.389 --> 05:08.187
Haven't you ever developed
an interest in something

05:08.266 --> 05:09.734
that you didn't
initially think

05:09.893 --> 05:11.315
you were gonna develop
an interest in?

05:11.394 --> 05:12.486
Um...

05:12.562 --> 05:14.189
No, not really.

05:16.316 --> 05:18.444
Haven't you ever...

05:19.736 --> 05:21.864
Haven't you ever been put
in a new situation

05:21.947 --> 05:25.497
and found that after
overcoming its difficulties,

05:25.575 --> 05:27.669
you had developed
a new set of skills

05:27.744 --> 05:29.542
and new experiences
along the way?

05:29.621 --> 05:31.339
No, I really haven't.

05:31.706 --> 05:32.707
Okay.

05:32.833 --> 05:35.427
Anyway, it was open-book.

05:35.627 --> 05:39.177
So, what's the difference
between using a book

05:39.256 --> 05:41.679
and, like, I don't know,
using somebody else's mind

05:41.758 --> 05:43.101
who's really
good at math?

05:43.176 --> 05:45.895
I mean, it's not like this person
did the whole test for me.

05:45.971 --> 05:47.063
Oh, no?

05:47.180 --> 05:48.272
No, I did some of it.

05:48.849 --> 05:51.773
Well, next time I'd appreciate
it if you did it all.

05:52.936 --> 05:53.937
Okay?

05:54.271 --> 05:55.773
You are so fair.

05:58.483 --> 05:59.826
What did he
say to you?

06:01.027 --> 06:02.028
Nothing.

06:02.237 --> 06:05.116
Mr. Aaron and I have an understanding
about my math problem.

06:05.782 --> 06:09.582
So the President of the
United States, William B. McKinley,

06:09.744 --> 06:13.248
authorizes the use of private
detectives to break the strike

06:13.748 --> 06:16.001
and they went out there
and shot 'em down!

06:16.626 --> 06:18.378
Just like they
did in Virginia,

06:18.461 --> 06:20.555
just like they
did in Pennsylvania.

06:20.630 --> 06:22.052
Because they didn't care!

06:22.841 --> 06:24.343
They did not care!

06:25.176 --> 06:26.644
And that's basically it.

06:27.637 --> 06:29.639
That's basically
all there is to say.

06:30.140 --> 06:31.767
All right? Go ahead.

06:31.850 --> 06:33.648
- Becky.
- Well...

06:33.977 --> 06:36.025
Mr. Klein! I mean,
was there ever, like,

06:36.146 --> 06:38.194
a good president of
the United States?

06:39.566 --> 06:40.909
I don't
know, Becky.

06:41.026 --> 06:42.369
I think that's
a good question.

06:42.444 --> 06:43.946
What do you think?

06:45.488 --> 06:47.161
You. Lionel.
What do you think?

06:47.324 --> 06:48.997
Did we ever have
a good president?

06:49.826 --> 06:51.920
Um... I don't know.

06:52.412 --> 06:55.291
I guess most of them have just
been, like, totally corrupt.

06:56.791 --> 06:57.792
Lisa?

06:58.001 --> 07:01.050
Can I just say that I'm not
necessarily, like, a big fan

07:01.129 --> 07:03.632
of all the presidents
of the United States,

07:03.715 --> 07:05.513
especially the current one.

07:05.592 --> 07:07.686
But I still don't think it's
necessarily all that useful

07:07.761 --> 07:10.605
to categorize every president
as universally corrupt,

07:10.680 --> 07:13.229
because that just seems
really general to me.

07:13.308 --> 07:15.561
